Skill plans
Year 7 English
IXL offers more than 100 year 7 English skills to explore and learn! Not sure where to start? Go to your personalised Recommendations wall to find skills picked just for you, or select a skill plan that aligns to your textbook, territory curriculum or standardised test.

Reading strategies  Writing strategies  Vocabulary  Grammar and mechanics 
Reading strategies
A.	Main idea
1	Determine the main idea of a passage (72)
B.	Theme
1	Match the quotations with their themes (71)
2	Determine the themes of short stories (71)
C.	Author's purpose and tone
1	Identify the author's purpose (70)
2	Which sentence is more formal? (100) Medal
3	Compare passages for tone (90) Proficiency Ribbon
D.	Point of view
1	Determine the author's point of view (80) Proficiency Ribbon
 
E.	Text structure
1	Compare and contrast in informational texts (71)
2	Match causes and effects in informational texts (68)
3	Match problems with their solutions (64)
4	Identify text structures (63)
F.	Literary devices
1	Interpret the meaning of an allusion from its source (68)
2	Recall the source of an allusion (76)
3	Interpret figures of speech (60)
4	Classify figures of speech (64)
5	Analyse the effects of figures of speech on meaning and tone (69)
 
G.	Analysing literature
1	Analyse short stories (65)
H.	Analysing informational texts
1	Read and understand informational passages (61)
2	Trace an argument (61)
I.	Comparing texts
1	Compare two texts with different genres (60)
J.	Visual elements
1	Compare illustrations of literary and historical subjects (100) Medal
Writing strategies
K.	Organising writing
1	Order topics from broadest to narrowest (71)
2	Organise information by topic (75)
3	Transitions with conjunctive adverbs (60)
 
L.	Developing and supporting arguments
1	Distinguish facts from opinions (64)
2	Choose evidence to support a claim (64)
3	Identify supporting details in informational texts (63)
4	Identify supporting details in literary texts (63)
5	Identify counterclaims (64)
M.	Creative techniques
1	Use personification (62)
 
N.	Editing and revising
1	Use parallel structure (90) Proficiency Ribbon
2	Remove redundant words or phrases (92) Proficiency Ribbon
3	Use the correct frequently confused word (65)
4	Correct errors with frequently confused words (72)
5	Suggest appropriate revisions (57)
O.	Research skills
1	Identify plagiarism (64)
Vocabulary
P.	Prefixes and suffixes
1	Words with pre- (67)
2	Words with re- (61)
3	Words with sub- (60)
4	Words with mis- (60)
5	Words with un-, dis-, in-, im- and non- (60)
6	Words with -ful (60)
7	Words with -less (60)
8	Words with -able and -ible (64)
Q.	Greek and Latin roots
1	Use Greek and Latin roots as clues to the meanings of words (60)
2	Use words as clues to the meanings of Greek and Latin roots (64)
3	Determine the meanings of Greek and Latin roots (67)
4	Determine the meanings of words with Greek and Latin roots (60)
 
R.	Synonyms and antonyms
1	Choose the synonym (65)
2	Choose the antonym (65)
S.	Homophones
1	Use the correct homophone (64)
2	Which definition matches the sentence? (64)
3	Which sentence matches the definition? (60)
T.	Shades of meaning
1	Describe the difference between related words (64)
2	Positive and negative connotation (65)
U.	Analogies
1	Analogies (67)
2	Analogies: challenge (61)
 
V.	Context clues
1	Find words using context (64)
2	Determine the meaning of words using synonyms in context (64)
3	Determine the meaning of words using antonyms in context (60)
4	Use context to identify the meaning of a word (59)
W.	Domain-specific vocabulary
1	Determine the meaning of domain-specific words with pictures (57)
X.	Reference skills
1	Alphabetical order (64)
2	Use guide words (62)
3	Use dictionary entries (62)
4	Use dictionary definitions (55)
5	Use thesaurus entries (63)
Grammar and mechanics
Y.	Sentences, fragments and run-ons
1	Is the sentence declarative, interrogative, imperative or exclamatory? (64)
2	Identify the complete subject or complete predicate of a sentence (63)
3	Identify the simple subject or simple predicate of a sentence (63)
4	Identify the compound subject or compound predicate of a sentence (63)
5	Is it a complete sentence or a fragment? (60)
6	Is it a complete sentence or a run-on? (61)
7	Is it a complete sentence, a fragment or a run-on? (62)
Z.	Phrases and clauses
1	Is it a phrase or a clause? (64)
2	Identify appositives and appositive phrases (62)
3	Identify dependent and independent clauses (64)
4	Is the sentence simple, compound, complex or compound-complex? (63)
5	Combine sentences using relative clauses (60)
AA.	Nouns
1	Form and use plurals: review (64)
2	Form and use plurals of compound nouns (59)
3	Identify plurals, singular possessives and plural possessives (59)
4	Form the singular or plural possessive (60)
5	Identify and correct errors with plural and possessive nouns (60)
BB.	Pronouns and antecedents
1	Identify pronouns and their antecedents (60)
2	Use the pronoun that agrees with the antecedent (59)
3	Identify vague pronoun references (62)
4	Identify all of the possible antecedents (58)
5	Correct inappropriate shifts in pronoun number and person (80) Proficiency Ribbon
 
CC.	Pronoun types
1	Choose between subject and object pronouns (60)
2	Compound subjects and objects with 'I' and 'me' (60)
3	Compound subjects and objects with pronouns (63)
4	Choose between personal and reflexive pronouns (57)
5	Use reflexive pronouns (60)
6	Is the pronoun reflexive or intensive? (63)
7	Use relative pronouns: who and whom (64)
8	Use relative pronouns: who, whom, whose, which and that (60)
DD.	Verb types
1	Identify transitive and intransitive verbs (64)
2	Identify linking verbs, predicate adjectives and predicate nouns (55)
EE.	Subject-verb agreement
1	Correct errors with subject-verb agreement (60)
2	Correct errors with indefinite pronoun-verb agreement (59)
3	Use the correct verb – with compound subjects (60)
FF.	Verb tense
1	Irregular past tense: review (60)
2	Simple past, present and future tense: review (59)
3	Identify and correct inappropriate shifts in verb tense (60)
4	Form the progressive verb tenses (60)
5	Form the perfect verb tenses (58)
GG.	Adjectives and adverbs
1	Identify adjectives (57)
2	Order adjectives (62)
3	Identify adverbs (47)
4	Choose between adjectives and adverbs (64)
5	Is the word an adjective or adverb? (61)
6	Form and use comparative and superlative adjectives (58)
7	Good, better, best, bad, worse and worst (62)
8	Form and use comparative and superlative adverbs (50)
9	Well, better, best, badly, worse and worst (60)
 
HH.	Prepositions
1	Identify prepositional phrases (61)
II.	Direct and indirect objects
1	Is it a direct object or an indirect object? (61)
JJ.	Conjunctions
1	Use the correct pair of correlative conjunctions (62)
KK.	Misplaced modifiers
1	Misplaced modifiers with pictures (62)
2	Select the misplaced or dangling modifier (58)
3	Are the modifiers used correctly? (56)
LL.	Restrictive and non-restrictive elements
1	What does the punctuation suggest? (60)
2	Commas with non-restrictive elements (51)
MM.	Commas
1	Commas with compound and complex sentences (60)
2	Commas with direct addresses, introductory words, interjections and interrupters (60)
3	Commas with coordinate adjectives (62)
NN.	Semicolons, colons and commas
1	Use semicolons and commas to separate clauses (54)
2	Use semicolons, colons and commas with lists (58)
OO.	Dashes, hyphens and ellipses
1	Use dashes (56)
2	Use hyphens in compound adjectives (55)
